{
  "id": "CMG_CSM.DF12_Springfuser_and_Flow_Control_Tubing",
  "cmg_number": "CSM.DF12",
  "title": "Springfuser and Flow Control Tubing",
  "version_date": null,
  "section": "Clinical Skill",
  "content_markdown": "#### Indications\n\n- Patients that require administration of medication as an infusion: \n- Amiodarone for VT, rapid AF or AFl, with output.\n- Magnesium for eclampsia.\n\n#### Procedure\n\n- Confirm “5 rights” with paramedic partner, **the right**: \n- Patient\n- Drug\n- Dose\n- Time\n- Route\n- Using a 10ml syringe, dilute the medication with the required volume of NaCl to give a total volume of 7mls.\n\n- Remove any air bubbles from the syringe and firmly attach flow control tubing.\n\n- Prime the tubing (approx 0.2mls).\n\n- Connect the flow control tubing to the patient’s cannula.\n\n- Insert the syringe plunger fully into the Springfuser unit, rotating the flange 90\\xb0 to lock into place (see **Figure 1**).\n\nFigure 1\n\n- Tape the Springfuser securely to the limb in line with the cannula.\n\n- Regularly reassess the cannula site for dislodgment, swelling, reddening or discomfort and the flow control tubing for kinks or blockages. If a blockage occurs, replace the tubing.\n\n#### Specific Notes\n\n- Always ensure medication pre administration checks are completed prior to any drug administration.",
